WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:20.680
 [MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:27.560
 Where in the Python 001 did you start building the objects?

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:31.600
 And where did the objects come first, and then a syntax came?

00:00:31.600 --> 00:00:34.040
 Or did you build a syntax, and then the objects?

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:42.440
 I think in my head, I had both.

00:00:42.440 --> 00:00:49.400
 Because I was building a stripped down version of ABC.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:55.540
 And I was very familiar with how ABC implemented

00:00:55.540 --> 00:00:57.840
 its data structures.

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:00.960
 And I had pretty well-developed ideas

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:08.560
 about how I would do it instead of the ABC way,

00:01:08.560 --> 00:01:13.320
 both for the syntax and for the data structures.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:18.920
 So for the syntax, actually, my main gripe about ABC

00:01:18.920 --> 00:01:25.720
 was that it used uppercase letters for the keywords

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:27.360
 of the language.

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:30.840
 They had a reason for that, but I

00:01:30.840 --> 00:01:32.600
 didn't think it was a good reason.

00:01:32.600 --> 00:01:39.880
 And it just looked horrible to a Unix hacker like myself.

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:44.160
 So that's what I wanted to change for the syntax.

00:01:44.160 --> 00:01:46.600
 But I knew that I wanted to do the indentation.

00:01:46.600 --> 00:01:52.360
 And I had already participated in the parser for ABC,

00:01:52.360 --> 00:01:54.000
 so I knew how to do that stuff.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
 I had some of my own ideas, but I knew what I wanted.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:06.240
 I literally actually started with a parser.

00:02:06.240 --> 00:02:10.200
 And actually, I started with a lexer and a parser.

00:02:10.200 --> 00:02:13.000
 Those were actually the first bits of the language

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:13.800
 that I wrote.

00:02:13.800 --> 00:02:20.200
 But before I started, I knew I had very specific ideas

00:02:20.200 --> 00:02:25.720
 on how the primitive data types would be implemented.

00:02:25.720 --> 00:02:29.760
 I would use the same reference count mechanism

00:02:29.760 --> 00:02:31.360
 that I knew well from ABC.

00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:39.320
 I would implement integers in a similar way,

00:02:39.320 --> 00:02:43.820
 because I wanted--

00:02:43.820 --> 00:02:48.160
 Integers would be an easy choice not to put in the object.

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:52.320
 Yeah, I wanted everything to be an object.

00:02:52.320 --> 00:02:57.800
 That was also a thing I approved of about ABC.

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:00.480
 And I think I have to take it back

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:04.400
 about the arbitrary precision integers.

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:07.400
 Those came quickly, but I don't think

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:11.800
 that they came immediately.

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:15.200
 There was an integer type, which was 32 bits.

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:17.720
 There was a separate long type, which

00:03:17.720 --> 00:03:20.720
 survived until the end of Python 2,

00:03:20.720 --> 00:03:22.320
 which was arbitrary precision.

00:03:22.320 --> 00:03:25.240
 And there was a flow type.

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:30.960
 Then for the more complex data structures--

00:03:30.960 --> 00:03:36.360
 and the numeric types were not all that different

00:03:36.360 --> 00:03:41.160
 or interesting, not that different from ABC.

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:47.680
 But for the rest, I sort of had seen

00:03:47.680 --> 00:03:51.600
 what ABC did, which was that everything was implemented

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:54.360
 as a tree, even strings.

00:03:54.360 --> 00:03:57.520
 And I did not like that, because I

00:03:57.520 --> 00:04:02.000
 wanted to interface with system calls and C libraries.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:08.600
 And I said, I want strings to be arbitrary length,

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:11.560
 but I want them to be a linear buffer.

00:04:11.560 --> 00:04:17.440
 And so too bad if one string sort of requires

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:21.640
 allocating a large buffer at once.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:23.760
 Most strings aren't that long.

00:04:23.760 --> 00:04:25.880
 I'll make sure that it works for any size.

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:30.800
 But I'll optimize for the short strings that

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:33.160
 are the bread and butter of so many programs

00:04:33.160 --> 00:04:36.440
 I imagine would be written in Python.

00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:40.760
 That is a brilliant choice, but not automatic or intuitive,

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:43.720
 that that would be the right answer.

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:47.800
 Having sort of written a lot of C code

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:52.400
 and knowing that I wanted Python to be extensible with C,

00:04:52.400 --> 00:04:57.000
 that was also one of the very early choices.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:03.840
 I wanted to sort of link back to C code in a natural way.

00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:08.480
 So the import system was part of that.

00:05:08.480 --> 00:05:13.520
 So when Python was a month old or maybe two months old,

00:05:13.520 --> 00:05:16.600
 if you were appending to a string in a loop,

00:05:16.600 --> 00:05:21.200
 was it basically extending, reallocating, and copying?

00:05:21.200 --> 00:05:23.920
 Now, strings were always immutable.

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:29.840
 Sorry, yes, it was calculating the size of the result,

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:33.360
 allocating a new string object, and then copying

00:05:33.360 --> 00:05:36.080
 the two originals into that.

00:05:36.080 --> 00:05:39.400
 There is a string resize internal operation

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:45.160
 that is sort of intended to be only used when you're building

00:05:45.160 --> 00:05:48.800
 up a string before you've shown it to anyone else.

00:05:48.800 --> 00:05:54.400
 And I needed that because I was envisioning an I/O system

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.800
 where you say, oh, I'm going to read a line

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:00.200
 and I don't know how long that line is going to be,

00:06:00.200 --> 00:06:02.480
 or maybe I'm going to slurp an entire file

00:06:02.480 --> 00:06:06.440
 into a single string and I don't know how long that file is.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:10.280
 So I'm allocating a large enough buffer.

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:12.740
 I'm reading into that buffer.

00:06:12.740 --> 00:06:16.600
 And then if it turns out that I allocated 1,000 bytes,

00:06:16.600 --> 00:06:19.200
 but what I read was only 15 bytes,

00:06:19.200 --> 00:06:24.040
 I reallocated to give the sort of remaining 85 or whatever,

00:06:24.040 --> 00:06:25.320
 900 bytes.

00:06:25.320 --> 00:06:27.800
 Are we talking about your thinking

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:31.200
 before you released the very first version of Python,

00:06:31.200 --> 00:06:32.440
 meaning you didn't like--

00:06:32.440 --> 00:06:34.160
 at some point, you came back from vacation

00:06:34.160 --> 00:06:36.800
 and you handed it to somebody at work.

00:06:36.800 --> 00:06:41.160
 This is your thinking when there's only one person before

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:42.600
 even the 0.01--

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:45.280
 Oh, yeah, yeah.

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:48.240
 I wanted strings to be done that way,

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:51.640
 including the little detail that if you

00:06:51.640 --> 00:06:57.520
 have a string of, say, 10 bytes, you allocate 11 bytes

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:00.200
 and you put a no byte at the end,

00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:05.840
 just so that if you happen to want to pass that string

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:09.040
 to a C library function that expected

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:13.640
 zero terminated strings, no byte terminated strings,

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:15.720
 you wouldn't have to copy it.

00:07:15.720 --> 00:07:17.440
 There might be a no byte in the middle,

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:20.200
 so things might still go wrong.

00:07:20.200 --> 00:07:26.840
 But if you sort of knew or trusted that that wasn't the case,

00:07:26.840 --> 00:07:31.360
 you wouldn't have to make a copy with one extra byte

00:07:31.360 --> 00:07:33.560
 just to make sure that that no byte was there.

00:07:33.560 --> 00:07:37.080
 The no byte is part of the data structure, only, of course,

00:07:37.080 --> 00:07:39.880
 visible on the C side.

00:07:39.880 --> 00:07:42.320
 So for lists, I had a similar idea.

00:07:42.320 --> 00:07:48.500
 Again, lists in ABC were a tree structure

00:07:48.500 --> 00:07:53.480
 that was sort of super efficient,

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:58.920
 even if you grew a very large list from small ones.

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.680
 And I thought that tree structure was way too complicated,

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:06.680
 so I said, OK, a list is a mutable data structure.

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:10.880
 That was sort of a concept that didn't really exist in ABC.

00:08:10.880 --> 00:08:13.600
 In ABC, everything was immutable.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:17.520
 I thought, well, pragmatically speaking,

00:08:17.520 --> 00:08:20.200
 I prefer my larger data structures,

00:08:20.200 --> 00:08:23.600
 meaning lists and dictionaries, to be mutable.

00:08:23.600 --> 00:08:25.120
 And so the list was--

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:28.760
 the implementation was always just a pointer

00:08:28.760 --> 00:08:32.800
 to a buffer that could be reallocated.

00:08:32.800 --> 00:08:35.000
 We call it list in Python.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:40.400
 It really is an array that just is an array of pointers.

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:42.560
 And each pointer points to an object.

00:08:42.560 --> 00:08:44.360
 We know how long that array is.

00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:45.980
 That's in the object header.

00:08:45.980 --> 00:08:49.960
 And so if there's no room, we reallocate it.

00:08:49.960 --> 00:08:53.200
 And if we throw something away from the middle,

00:08:53.200 --> 00:08:58.600
 then we shift everything over, and we also reallocate.

00:08:58.600 --> 00:09:01.200
 The only improvement that happened

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:05.000
 to that data structure in the last, well,

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:11.560
 let's say, 34 years is that the original implementation did not

00:09:11.560 --> 00:09:13.840
 have over allocation.

00:09:13.840 --> 00:09:18.420
 I was relying on realloc doing some kind of chunking.

00:09:18.420 --> 00:09:24.720
 So if you realloc something from 1,000 bytes to 1,004 bytes,

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:28.120
 I imagine, well, internally, realloc probably

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:33.120
 aligns everything in chunks of 16 bytes or more.

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:37.040
 And so it's not going to move that memory in that sort of--

00:09:37.040 --> 00:09:41.800
 eventually, that was shown to be either false or just

00:09:41.800 --> 00:09:43.120
 inefficient.

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:45.800
 You assumed realloc would do it as well as you would have done

00:09:45.800 --> 00:09:48.480
 it, but eventually, it didn't.

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:49.800
 It didn't, yeah.

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:54.240
 And so eventually, there are sort of internally,

00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:59.080
 there are two sizes that are held in the list object header.

00:09:59.080 --> 00:10:02.720
 One tells you what the length of the array

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.720
 is of the list is to the Python user,

00:10:05.720 --> 00:10:09.080
 and the other one tells you how much space there

00:10:09.080 --> 00:10:12.520
 is in the array, and the second is always larger than the first.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:13.960
 And then--

00:10:13.960 --> 00:10:16.520
 I'm shocked that it wasn't a linked list.

00:10:16.520 --> 00:10:17.080
 Oh, really?

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:18.360
 Yeah, I'm shocked.

00:10:18.360 --> 00:10:19.440
 Oh, I'm sorry.

00:10:19.440 --> 00:10:20.320
 It's named list.

00:10:20.320 --> 00:10:23.920
 But OK.

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:26.240
 Yeah, I know.

00:10:26.240 --> 00:10:27.400
 I get what you're doing.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:31.560
 So then talk through, as you built the earliest dictionary

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:35.360
 structure, what's different between that?

00:10:35.360 --> 00:10:40.760
 So again, in ABC, dictionaries were trees,

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:44.800
 and in the case of dictionaries,

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:47.400
 they were kept in sorted order by the key.

00:10:47.400 --> 00:10:52.320
 The key was always some orderable object.

00:10:52.320 --> 00:10:57.160
 Well, I think in ABC, everything was comparable.

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:00.200
 At least two things of the same type.

00:11:00.200 --> 00:11:05.800
 So ABC-- and again, I thought that was too complex,

00:11:05.800 --> 00:11:12.680
 and I had skimmed at least Knuth volume 3, which explains

00:11:12.680 --> 00:11:15.360
 the concept of hash tables.

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:19.960
 And I was familiar with hash tables in Perl,

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.880
 where I think they're called hashes.

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:26.480
 And so I just sort of--

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:30.280
 I leafed through the table of contents of Knuth volume 3,

00:11:30.280 --> 00:11:35.680
 and I picked a hashing algorithm and sort of a hash table

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:38.240
 organization that felt right.

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:45.440
 And so I chose open hashing instead of sort

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:50.400
 of having separate linked lists for buckets.

00:11:50.400 --> 00:11:54.520
 And the original hash algorithm for strings, at least,

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:56.600
 was something-- I don't know if I

00:11:56.600 --> 00:11:59.640
 picked the hash function out of Knuth also,

00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:01.440
 but I probably did.

00:12:01.440 --> 00:12:03.960
 Between Python 3.7 and Python 3.8,

00:12:03.960 --> 00:12:07.520
 dictionaries kept their order.

00:12:07.520 --> 00:12:08.480
 Ah.

00:12:08.480 --> 00:12:10.120
 Ah.

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:11.800
 Like, what happened?

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:13.920
 Was it the revenge of ABC?

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:15.120
 You know, meaning that trees--

00:12:15.120 --> 00:12:16.800
 No.

00:12:16.800 --> 00:12:19.880
 So it's a different kind of order.

00:12:19.880 --> 00:12:22.960
 In ABC, the keys were sorted.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:32.360
 So if you have numeric keys, if you have the 1, 12, and 500

00:12:32.360 --> 00:12:36.880
 in your dictionary, in ABC at least,

00:12:36.880 --> 00:12:42.280
 the keys are ordered 1, 12, 500, or 1, 2, 3, or whatever.

00:12:42.280 --> 00:12:47.560
 And if you insert 11, it gets inserted between 1 and 12.

00:12:47.560 --> 00:12:51.760
 On the other hand, in the newer Python dictionaries

00:12:51.760 --> 00:12:57.400
 that preserve order, it is insertion order.

00:12:57.400 --> 00:13:01.840
 So it is not made-- because the sort of--

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:04.600
 Python dictionaries don't require

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:09.440
 that the key type is sortable, is comparable.

00:13:09.440 --> 00:13:12.600
 It only needs to be hashable.

00:13:12.600 --> 00:13:16.880
 And so we can-- well, and of course, it needs to be--

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:21.120
 you need to have an equality comparison.

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:23.040
 Is this string equal to that string?

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:26.000
 But you don't need-- you never need to look at,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.440
 is this string less than that string?

00:13:29.440 --> 00:13:34.280
 So what did you do to make it keep insertion order?

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:39.000
 So that was in a time when I had long relinquished

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:45.600
 or delegated development of most of the basic data types.

00:13:45.600 --> 00:13:48.240
 I think we had a developer in Japan

00:13:48.240 --> 00:13:54.800
 who for years had been improving the efficiency

00:13:54.800 --> 00:13:57.440
 of the dictionary type.

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:03.000
 And one of the problems of the original design

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.840
 with open hashing that I picked from Knuth

00:14:05.840 --> 00:14:08.900
 is that it's pretty space inefficient.

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:10.360
 Because if you have--

00:14:14.840 --> 00:14:19.900
 let's see if I can reconstruct-- for each key value pair,

00:14:19.900 --> 00:14:24.640
 you have to have a pointer to the key.

00:14:24.640 --> 00:14:27.960
 Let's be old-fashioned and say that's four bytes.

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:29.480
 You have a pointer to the value.

00:14:29.480 --> 00:14:31.400
 That's another four bytes.

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:35.600
 Then you have the hash, which is another four bytes.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:41.000
 So now the hash table is an array of structs

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:43.720
 that are each 12 bytes long.

00:14:43.720 --> 00:14:49.240
 And for the hash table algorithm to the lookup and insertion

00:14:49.240 --> 00:14:53.360
 and deletion algorithm to work at all,

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:58.480
 you can't have the table be more than 2/3 full.

00:14:58.480 --> 00:15:05.040
 So that means that if you have an array of 1,000 entries,

00:15:05.040 --> 00:15:10.560
 you can store at most 600 or 700 key value pairs.

00:15:10.560 --> 00:15:19.240
 And so you have 300 or 400 times 24 bytes wasted space.

00:15:19.240 --> 00:15:25.920
 And so our Japanese core dev figured out

00:15:25.920 --> 00:15:33.720
 a way to have separate tables where the hash table only

00:15:33.720 --> 00:15:41.080
 contained one thing and the actual key value pairs

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:47.480
 and hashes were kept in a table that had no holes in it.

00:15:47.480 --> 00:15:51.500
 So they were basically kind of growing, filling, remembering.

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:54.600
 Everything is remembering where things are laid out.

00:15:54.600 --> 00:15:59.560
 And so first, he stumbled upon sort of--

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:04.600
 I think he refined the algorithm a few times,

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:06.940
 having these separate arrays.

00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:12.000
 And then he stumbled upon the property that, oh, hey,

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.120
 it happens to preserve insertion order.

00:16:15.120 --> 00:16:17.600
 In the second table, for sure, right?

00:16:17.600 --> 00:16:20.280
 Exactly, in the second table.

00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:23.720
 Because the sort of the table in which you jump around

00:16:23.720 --> 00:16:30.480
 based on the hash value now just has an index

00:16:30.480 --> 00:16:33.480
 in into the other table.

00:16:33.480 --> 00:16:36.040
 And so there is an additional space saving.

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:43.680
 Because if your hash table has less than 256 elements,

00:16:43.680 --> 00:16:48.480
 that array only needs to have one byte for the index.

00:16:48.480 --> 00:16:53.440
 And so there is like all kinds of cleverness there.

00:16:53.440 --> 00:16:58.200
 It comes as a surprise to me that you don't do linked lists.

00:16:58.200 --> 00:16:59.280
 Really?

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:02.360
 I could have told you that 10 years ago.

00:17:02.360 --> 00:17:04.960
 That it doesn't do linked lists.

00:17:04.960 --> 00:17:06.600
 I mean, I guess, and that has probably

00:17:06.600 --> 00:17:10.920
 to do with your desire to interoperate the seed kind of

00:17:10.920 --> 00:17:15.040
 just percolates through about blocks of things

00:17:15.040 --> 00:17:17.960
 that can be extended and then filled in

00:17:17.960 --> 00:17:21.080
 seem to be better than generic linked lists.

00:17:21.080 --> 00:17:25.720
 What I didn't know at the time that that's also

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:28.920
 a good architecture for modern hardware,

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:34.520
 because you have better cache locality, which is not

00:17:34.520 --> 00:17:41.880
 a concept that I think I even knew existed in '89.

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:45.520
 So I think I just avoided linked lists

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:48.200
 because I didn't like them for some other reason.

00:17:48.200 --> 00:17:49.200
 That's cool.

00:17:49.200 --> 00:17:52.000
 That's exactly-- well, it's not exactly what I hoped you'd say.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.640
 I'd hope you'd do linked lists over and over and over again,

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:57.000
 because I just have assumed all my life that linked lists

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.000
 are the--

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:00.720
 linked lists and hash maps and linked lists on top of hash maps

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:02.600
 and linked lists, linked lists, linked lists.

00:18:02.600 --> 00:18:05.480
 Because computer science thinks about linked lists all the time.

00:18:05.480 --> 00:18:08.920
 There are plenty of pointers in Python,

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:13.360
 but sort of the classic linked list is not used much.

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:22.560
 [MUSIC PLAYING]

